n, show that finance as we know it today emerged gradually in the late nineteenth century and only coalesced after World War II, becoming ever more complicated—and ever more central to the American economy. The authors explain the models, regulations, and institutions at the heart of modern finance and uncover the complex and sometimes surprising origins of its critical features, such as corporate accounting standards, the Federal Reserve System, risk management practices, and American Keynesian and New Classic monetary economics. This book sees finance through its highs and lows, from pre-Depression to post-Recession, exploring the myriad ways in which the practices of finance and the realities of the economy influenced one another through the years. A masterwork of collaboration, Finance in America lays bare the theories and practices that constitute finance, opening up the discussion of its role and risks to a broad range of scholars and citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEconomicszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFinancezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFinancezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aFinance--United States--History--20th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican finance.  aGreat Depression.  afinancialization.  aglobal crisis of 2008.  ahistory of the discipline of finance.  aneoclassical economics.  aneoliberalism.  aoil shocks in the 1970s.  areal and financial sides of the economy.1 aPoovey, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226502212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226502212/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  Uni